<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06137226 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06137226 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  GILROY; MILITARY; MAN; INJURY; IRAQ; MEDICAL; REPORT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A Gilroy soldier severely burned when his tanker truck overturned and burstinto flames in Iraq is responding well to treatment but faces a long recovery,his family said Wednesday.;    Army Spec. 4 John Diaz Jr., 23, receivedsecond- and third-degree burns over 60 percent of his body, said his father,John Diaz Sr.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  BURNED IN IRAQ, GILROY SOLDIER IMPROVES  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The young man, a 1986 graduate of Gilroy High School, was flown to Germanyand has responded so well to treatment he may be flown today to an Army burnunit in San Antonio, Texas, his father said.;    The family was notified ofthe accident on Sunday, about seven hours after the soldier's gas tanker truckswerved to avoid an Iraqi taxi, overturned and burst into flames, his fathersaid.;    &quot;The first three days we went through hell, everyone was justpraying he'd pull through,&quot; Diaz said.;    He called it a miracle that his sonand another soldier in the truck got out at all. The other soldier died enroute to Germany, he said.;    He said he talked to his son's doctors inGermany and was told he has opened his eyes, is responding well and remains inserious to critical condition.;    &quot;He'll be gravely ill for a month or twoand then he'll require a least a year of hospitalization,&quot; Diaz said.;    Hesaid the burns are mostly on his legs, chest, back, arms and hands.;    Diazsaid the Army has called the family twice daily since the accident withupdates on his son's condition.;    &quot;They've been very good about it.&quot;;   Diaz entered the army after graduation and was stationed in Germany andawaiting deployment to the Persian Gulf war, his father said.;    When thefighting stopped, his unit was sent to northern Iraq to help set up refugeecamps for Kurds, he said.;    Diaz said he and his wife, who have two otherchildren, expect to fly to Texas this week to be with their son.;    He saidthe army offered to fly the family to Germany, but that became unnecessarywhen his son began responding to treatment and the decision was made to senthim to San Antonio.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  JACK FOLEY, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  South County  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910516  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  357  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday May 16, 199100137226,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>